an, 15th [[Prime Minister of Poland]] (b. 1867)\n*[[1944]] &ndash; [[Max Brand]], American journalist and author (b. 1892)\n*  1944   &ndash; [[Arthur Quiller-Couch]], English author, poet, and critic (b. 1863)\n*[[1956]] &ndash; [[Louis Calhern]], American actor and singer (b. 1895)\n*[[1957]] &ndash; [[Alfonso de Portago]], Spanish bobsledder and race car driver (b. 1928)\n*  1957   &ndash; [[Erich von Stroheim]], Austrian-American actor, director, and producer (b. 1885)\n*[[1963]] &ndash; [[Richard Girulatis]], German footballer and manager (b. 1878)\n* 1963  &ndash; [[Robert Kerr (athlete)|Robert Kerr]], Irish-Canadian sprinter and coach (b. 1882)\n*[[1964]] &ndash; [[Agnes Forbes Blackadder]], Scottish medical doctor (b. 1875)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universitystory.gla.ac.uk/ww1-biography/?id=1458|title=University of Glasgow :: Story :: Biography of Surgeon Agnes Forbes Blackadder|website=www.universitystory.gla.ac.uk|access-date=2019-12-30}}</ref>\n*[[1966]] &ndash; [[Felix Steiner]], Russian-German [[SS]] officer (b. 1896)\n*[[1967]] &ndash; [[John Masefield]], English poet and author (b. 1878)\n*[[1970]] &ndash; [[Nelly Sachs]], German poet and playwright, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (b. 1891)\n*[[1971]] &ndash; [[Heinie Manush]], American baseball player and coach (b. 1901)\n*[[1973]] &ndash; [[Frances Marion]], American screenwriter, novelist and journalist (b. 1888)\n*  1973   &ndash; [[Art Pollard]], American race car driver (b. 1927)\n*[[1974]] &ndash;  [[Wayne Maki]], Canadian [[National Hockey League]] player (b. 1944)\n*[[1980]] &ndash;  [[Lillian Roth]], American actress 9b. 1910)\n*[[1985]] &ndash; [[Jean Dubuffet]], French painter and sculptor (b. 1901)\n*[[1986]] &ndash; [[Elisabeth Bergner]], German actress (b. 1897)\n*[[1992]] &ndash; [[Nikos Gatsos]], Greek poet and songwriter (b. 1911)\n*  1992   &ndash; [[Robert Reed]], American actor (b. 1932)\n*[[1993]] &ndash; [[Zeno Col\u00f2]], Italian Olympic alpine skier (b.1920)\n*[[1994]] &ndash; [[Erik Erikson]], German-American psychologist and psychoanalyst (b. 1902)\n*  1994   &ndash; [[John Smith (Labour Party leader)|John Smith]], Scottish-English lawyer and politician, [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]] (b. 1938) \n*[[1995]] &ndash; [[\u0218tefan Kov\u00e1cs]], Romanian football player and coach (b. 1920)\n*[[1999]] &ndash; [[Saul Steinberg]], Romanian-American illustrator (b. 1914)\n*[[2000]] &ndash; [[Adam Petty]], American race car driver (b. 1980)\n*[[2001]] &ndash; [[Perry Como]], American singer and television host (b. 1912)\n*  2001   &ndash; [[Alexei Tupolev]], Russian engineer, designed the [[Tupolev Tu-144]] (b. 1925)\n*[[2003]] &ndash; [[Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan]], French-American diplomat (b. 1933)\n*[[2005]] &ndash; [[\u00d6mer Kavur]], Turkish director, producer, and screenwriter (b. 1944)\n*  2005   &ndash; [[Martin Lings]], English author and scholar (b. 1909)\n*  2005   &ndash; [[Monica Zetterlund]], Swedish actress (b. 1937)\n*[[2006]] &ndash; [[Hussein Maziq]], Libyan politician, [[Prime Minister of Libya]] (b. 1918)\n*[[2008]] &ndash; [[Robert Rauschenberg]], American painter and illustrator (b. 1925)\n*  2008   &ndash; [[Irena Sendler]], Polish nurse and humanitarian (b. 1910)\n*[[2009]] &ndash; [[Antonio Vega (singer)|Antonio Vega]], Spanish singer-songwriter and guitarist (b. 1957)\n*[[2012]] &ndash; [[Jan Bens]], Dutch footballer and coach (b. 1921)\n*  2012   &ndash; [[Eddy Paape]], Belgian illustrator (b. 1920)\n*[[2013]] &ndash; [[Gerd Langguth]], German political scientist, author, and academic (b. 1946)\n*[[2014]] &ndash; [[Cornell Borchers]], Lithuanian-German actress and singer (b. 1925)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Marco C\u00e9]], Italian cardinal (b. 1925)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[H. R. Giger]], Swiss painter, sculptor, and set designer (b. 1940)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Sarat Pujari]], Indian actor, director, and screenwriter (b. 1934)\n*  2014   &ndash; [[Lorenzo Zambrano]], Mexican businessman and philanthropist (b. 1944)\n*[[2015]] &ndash; [[Peter Gay]], German-American historian, author, and academic (b. 1923)\n*  2015   &ndash; [[William Zinsser]] American journalist and critic (b. 1922)\n*[[2016]] &ndash; [[Mike Agostini]], Trinidadian sprinter (b. 1935)\n*[[2017]] &ndash; [[Mauno Koivisto]], Finnish banker and politician, 9th President of Finland (b. 1923)\n*[[2018]] &ndash; [[Dennis Nilsen]], Scottish serial killer (b. 1945)\n<!--Do not add yourself or people without Wikipedia articles to this list. Do not trust \u201cthis year in history\u201d websites for accurate date information. Do not link multiple occurrences of the same year, just link the first occurrence.-->\n\n==Holidays and observances==\n*[[2nd Amendment Day]] ([[Pennsylvania]], United States)\n*Christian [[feast day]]:\n**Blessed [[Imelda Lambertini|Imelda]]\n**Blessed [[Joanna, Princess of Portugal|Joan of Portugal]]\n**[[Crispoldus]]\n**[[Dominic de la Calzada]]\n**[[Epiphanius of Salamis]]\n**[[Gregory Dix]] ([[Church of England]])\n**[[Saint Modoald|Modoald]]\n**[[Nereus, Achilleus, Domitilla, and Pancras]]\n**Patriarch [[Germanus I of Constantinople]] ([[Eastern Church]])\n**[[Philip of Agira]]\n**[[May 12 (Eastern Orthodox liturgics)]]\n*[[Day of the Finnish Identity]] ([[Finland]])\n*[[Chronic fatigue syndrome#Awareness day|International Myalgic Encephalomyelitis/Chronic Fatigue Syndrome Awareness Day]]\n*[[International Nurses Day]]\n*[[Public holidays in Georgia|Saint Andrea the First Day]] ([[Georgia (country)|Georgia]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/onthisday/hi/dates/stories/may/12 BBC: On This Day]\n* {{NYT On this day|month=05|day=12}}\n* [http://canadachannel.ca/todayincanadianhistory/index.php/May_12 Today in Canadian History]\n\n{{months}}\n\n[[Category:Days of the year]]\n[[Category:May]]\n", "name_user": "Googgoollman7777", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBirths:Removed unnecessary links.links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/May_12"}
{"title_page": "Kazys \u0160kirpa", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Kazys \u0160kirpa\n| image         = Kazys Skirpa.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1895|2|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = {{ill|Namaj\u016bnai|lt}}, [[Kovno Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1979|08|18|1895|2|18|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| burial_place  = [[Petra\u0161i\u016bnai Cemetery]] (reburied in 1995)\n| nationality   = Lithuanian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Military officer, diplomat\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Leader of the [[Lithuanian Activist Front]]\n| notable_works = \n| boards        = \n| alma_mater    = [[ETH Zurich|Institute of Technology in Zurich]] <br> Higher Military School in [[Kaunas]] <br> [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)]]\n| employer      = [[Lithuanian Army]] <br> Government of Lithuania <br> [[University of Dublin]] <br> [[Library of Congress]]\n| movement      =\n| party         =\n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n}}\n\n'''Kazys \u0160kirpa''' (18 February 1895 &ndash; 18 August 1979) was a Lithuanian military officer and diplomat. He is best known as the founder of the [[Lithuanian Activist Front]] (LAF) and his involvement in the attempt to establish [[June Uprising in Lithuania|Lithuanian independence in June 1941]].\n\n== Army career==\nDuring [[World War I]] he was mobilized into the Russian army and attempted to form Lithuanian detachments in [[Petrograd]]. After Lithuania declared independence in 1918, he returned and volunteered during the [[Lithuanian Wars of Independence]]. In 1920, as a member of the [[Lithuanian Peasant Popular Union]], he was elected to the [[Constituent Assembly of Lithuania]]. After that he decided to pursue a military education in [[ETH Zurich|Institute of Technology in Zurich]], Higher Military School in [[Kaunas]], and [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)]].<ref name=ignat/> Upon graduation in 1925, he worked as chief of the General Staff, but was forced to resign after the [[1926 Lithuanian coup d'\u00e9tat]], because he was actively refusing it and was trying to gather military force to protect the Government.\n\n== Political career==\nLater he served as a Lithuanian representative to Germany (1927\u20131930), [[League of Nations]] (1937), Poland (1938), and again Germany (1938\u20131941). After [[Soviet occupation of Lithuania|Soviet Union occupied Lithuania]] in 1940, \u0160kirpa fled to Germany and formed [[Lithuanian Activist Front]], a short-lived resistance organisation whose goal was to liberate Lithuania and re-establish its independence by working with the Nazis.<ref name=blood>Timothy Snyder - Bloodlands: Europe Between Hitler and Stalin, ch.6-Final Solution. 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-465-0-3147-4}}</ref> According to [[Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation]], he was a primary source of the secret part of the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] which he sent to the Latvian foreign minister {{Ill|Vilhelms Munters|lv|Vilhelms Munters}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.victimsofcommunism.org/witnessblog/2018/4/19/sg78hvjl0wlzrockaohia2vwmuiehd|title=Chekhov\u2019s Gun: The Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact in the Baltics|website=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> When [[Operation Barbarossa|Nazis invaded the Soviet Union]] in June 1941. He was named prime minister in the [[Provisional Government of Lithuania]]; however, the Germans placed him under [[house arrest]] and did not allow him to leave for Lithuania.<ref>{{cite web| first=Teres\u0117 Birut\u0117 |last=Burauskait\u0117 |url=http://genocid.lt/UserFiles/File/Pazymos/201510_skirpa_pazyma01.pdf |title=Kazio \u0160kirpos veikl\u0105 Antrojo pasaulinio karo metais |date=2016-01-05 |publisher=[[Genocide and Resistance Research Centre of Lithuania]] |accessdate=2016-10-22 }}</ref> From Berlin he moved to southern Germany and was allowed a short visit to Kaunas only in October 1943.<ref name=ignat/>  In June 1944, he was arrested for sending a memorandum to the Nazi officials asking to replace German authorities in Lithuania with a Lithuanian government. He was first imprisoned in a concentration camp in [[Bad Godesberg]] and in February 1945 moved to {{illm|Jeze\u0159\u00ed Castle|de|Schloss Jeze\u0159\u00ed}}.<ref name=ignat>{{cite journal|first1=Stasys |last1=Ignatavi\u010dius |first2=Gintautas |last2=Tamulaitis |url=http://www.lpkts.lt/sites/default/files/Trem_07.pdf |title=Pirmasis Lietuvos kariuomen\u0117s savanoris |date=20 February 2015 |volume=7 |issue=1125 |journal=Tremtinys |language=lt |page=5 |issn=2029-509X}}</ref>\n\n==Later life ==\nAfter the war, he went to Paris and from there to [[Dublin]], where he taught Russian language at the [[University of Dublin]].<ref name=ignat/> In 1949, he emigrated to the United States. He worked at the [[Library of Congress]]. In 1975 his memoir book about the 1941 independence movement was published. Originally interred in [[Washington, D.C.]], his remains were returned to [[Kaunas]] in June 1995, where he was reburied in [[Petra\u0161i\u016bnai Cemetery]].<ref name=ignat/> His re-burial was attended by then Lithuanian Defense Minister Linas Linkevi\u010dius.\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite encyclopedia | editor=Simas Su\u017eied\u0117lis | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia Lituanica]] | title=\u0160kirpa, Kazys | year=1970\u20131978 | publisher=Juozas Kapo\u010dius | volume=V | location=Boston, Massachusetts | id={{LCC | 74-114275}} | pages=206}}\n* {{cite web| url=http://www3.lrs.lt/pls/inter/w5_show?p_r=4160&p_d=2792&p_k=1 |title=Kazys \u0160kirpa | publisher=[[Seimas]] |date=2006-02-22 |accessdate=2008-03-29|language=lt}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skirpa, Kazys}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Pasvalys District Municipality]]\n[[Category:People from Kovno Governorate]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Lithuania to Germany]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian diplomats]]\n[[Category:Russian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Kazys \u0160kirpa\n| image         = Kazys Skirpa.png\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1895|2|18|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = {{ill|Namaj\u016bnai|lt}}, [[Kovno Governorate]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1979|08|18|1895|2|18|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]], [[United States]]\n| burial_place  = [[Petra\u0161i\u016bnai Cemetery]] (reburied in 1995)\n| nationality   = Lithuanian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Military officer, diplomat\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = Leader of the [[Lithuanian Activist Front]]\n| notable_works = \n| boards        = \n| alma_mater    = [[ETH Zurich|Institute of Technology in Zurich]] <br> Higher Military School in [[Kaunas]] <br> [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)]]\n| employer      = [[Lithuanian Army]] <br> Government of Lithuania <br> [[University of Dublin]] <br> [[Library of Congress]]\n| movement      =\n| party         =\n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n}}\n\n'''Kazys \u0160kirpa''' (18 February 1895 &ndash; 18 August 1979) was a Lithuanian military officer and diplomat. He is best known as the founder of the [[Lithuanian Activist Front]] (LAF) and his involvement in the attempt to establish [[June Uprising in Lithuania|Lithuanian independence in June 1941]].\n\n== Army career==\nDuring [[World War I]] he was mobilized into the Russian army and attempted to form Lithuanian detachments in [[Petrograd]]. After Lithuania declared independence in 1918, he returned and volunteered during the [[Lithuanian Wars of Independence]]. In 1920, as a member of the [[Lithuanian Peasant Popular Union]], he was elected to the [[Constituent Assembly of Lithuania]]. After that he decided to pursue a military education in [[ETH Zurich|Institute of Technology in Zurich]], Higher Military School in [[Kaunas]], and [[Royal Military Academy (Belgium)]].<ref name=ignat/> Upon graduation in 1925, he worked as chief of the General Staff, but was forced to resign after the [[1926 Lithuanian coup d'\u00e9tat]], because he was actively refusing it and was trying to gather military force to protect the Government.\n\n== Political career==\nLater he served as a Lithuanian representative to Germany (1927\u20131930), [[League of Nations]] (1937), Poland (1938), and again Germany (1938\u20131941). After [[Soviet occupation of Lithuania|Soviet Union occupied Lithuania]] in 1940, \u0160kirpa fled to Germany and formed [[Lithuanian Activist Front]], a short-lived resistance organisation whose goal was to liberate Lithuania and re-establish its independence by working with the Nazis.<ref name=blood>Timothy Snyder - Bloodlands: Europe Between Hitler and Stalin, ch.6-Final Solution. 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-465-0-3147-4}}</ref> According to [[Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation]], he was a primary source of the secret part of the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] which he sent to the Latvian foreign minister {{Ill|Vilhelms Munters|lv|Vilhelms Munters}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.victimsofcommunism.org/witnessblog/2018/4/19/sg78hvjl0wlzrockaohia2vwmuiehd|title=Chekhov\u2019s Gun: The Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact in the Baltics|website=Victims of Communism Memorial Foundation|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> When [[Operation Barbarossa|Nazis invaded the Soviet Union]] in June 1941, LAF cooperated with the Nazis and killed many [[Lithuanian Jews]] (see [[the Holocaust in Lithuania]]).<ref name=blood/> He was named prime minister in the [[Provisional Government of Lithuania]]; however, the Germans placed him under [[house arrest]] and did not allow him to leave for Lithuania.<ref>{{cite web| first=Teres\u0117 Birut\u0117 |last=Burauskait\u0117 |url=http://genocid.lt/UserFiles/File/Pazymos/201510_skirpa_pazyma01.pdf |title=Kazio \u0160kirpos veikl\u0105 Antrojo pasaulinio karo metais |date=2016-01-05 |publisher=[[Genocide and Resistance Research Centre of Lithuania]] |accessdate=2016-10-22 }}</ref> From Berlin he moved to southern Germany and was allowed a short visit to Kaunas only in October 1943.<ref name=ignat/>  In June 1944, he was arrested for sending a memorandum to the Nazi officials asking to replace German authorities in Lithuania with a Lithuanian government. He was first imprisoned in a concentration camp in [[Bad Godesberg]] and in February 1945 moved to {{illm|Jeze\u0159\u00ed Castle|de|Schloss Jeze\u0159\u00ed}}.<ref name=ignat>{{cite journal|first1=Stasys |last1=Ignatavi\u010dius |first2=Gintautas |last2=Tamulaitis |url=http://www.lpkts.lt/sites/default/files/Trem_07.pdf |title=Pirmasis Lietuvos kariuomen\u0117s savanoris |date=20 February 2015 |volume=7 |issue=1125 |journal=Tremtinys |language=lt |page=5 |issn=2029-509X}}</ref>\n\n==Later life ==\nAfter the war, he went to Paris and from there to [[Dublin]], where he taught Russian language at the [[University of Dublin]].<ref name=ignat/> In 1949, he emigrated to the United States. He worked at the [[Library of Congress]]. In 1975 his memoir book about the 1941 independence movement was published. Originally interred in [[Washington, D.C.]], his remains were returned to [[Kaunas]] in June 1995, where he was reburied in [[Petra\u0161i\u016bnai Cemetery]].<ref name=ignat/> His re-burial was attended by then Lithuanian Defense Minister Linas Linkevi\u010dius.\n\n==Street names==\nDue to \u0160kirpa's alleged anti-Semitic rhetoric as the leader of LAF, a movement to remove street names in both Kaunas and Vilnius in honor of \u0160kirpa was launched by British member of the Vilnius City Council [[Mark Adam Harold]]. \u0160kirpa was defended by [[Teres\u0117 Birut\u0117 Burauskait\u0117]] of the [[Genocide and Resistance Research Centre of Lithuania]] (LGGRTC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://defendinghistory.com/documents-which-argue-for-ethnic-cleansing-by-kazys-skirpa-stasys-rastikis-stasys-lozoraitis-and-petras-klimas-in-1940-1941-and-by-birute-terese-burauskaite-in-2015/78459|title=Documents Which Argue for Ethnic Cleansing (by Kazys \u0160kirpa, Stasys Ra\u0161tikis, Stasys Lozoraitis and Petras Klimas in 1940-1941 and by Birut\u0117 Teres\u0117 Burauskait\u0117 in 2015)|last=Kulinauskas|first=Andrius|date=2015-12-18}}</ref> Following reports in foreign press,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2017/apr/11/lithuanias-holocaust-past-still-haunts-country/|title=Surmounting Lithuania\u2019s Holocaust past|last=http://www.washingtontimes.com|first=The Washington Times|website=The Washington Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> and a campaign led from Los Angeles by Grant Arthur Gochin,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.jpost.com/Opinion/Will-Lithuania-continue-to-honor-Nazi-collaborators-412701|title=Will Lithuania continue to honor Nazi collaborators? - Opinion - Jerusalem Post|website=www.jpost.com|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref> the street name in Vilnius has been changed to \"Trispalv\u0117s\" (\"Tricolour\", a reference to the [[flag of Lithuania]]) by the Vilnius municipality on 24 July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrt.lt/naujienos/lietuvoje/2/1081731/sostines-taryba-apsisprende-skirpos-aleja-pervadina-i-trispalves|title=Sostin\u0117s taryba apsisprend\u0117: \u0160kirpos al\u0117j\u0105 pervadina \u012f Trispalv\u0117s|date=2019-07-24|website=lrt.lt|language=lt|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite encyclopedia | editor=Simas Su\u017eied\u0117lis | encyclopedia=[[Encyclopedia Lituanica]] | title=\u0160kirpa, Kazys | year=1970\u20131978 | publisher=Juozas Kapo\u010dius | volume=V | location=Boston, Massachusetts | id={{LCC | 74-114275}} | pages=206}}\n* {{cite web| url=http://www3.lrs.lt/pls/inter/w5_show?p_r=4160&p_d=2792&p_k=1 |title=Kazys \u0160kirpa | publisher=[[Seimas]] |date=2006-02-22 |accessdate=2008-03-29|language=lt}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skirpa, Kazys}}\n[[Category:1895 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Pasvalys District Municipality]]\n[[Category:People from Kovno Governorate]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Lithuania]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Lithuania to Germany]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian diplomats]]\n[[Category:Russian military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian people of World War II]]\n[[Category:Nazi concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:Lithuanian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Independence activists]]\n", "name_user": "Aidas00", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Non-encyclopedic information removed: political disputes have no place in the encyclopedia.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kazys_%C5%A0kirpa"}
{"title_page": "Edward Campbell (journalist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n:''For other persons named Edward Campbell, see [[Edward Campbell (disambiguation)]]''\n'''Edward Cranston Campbell''' (26 August 1916, [[Glasgow]] \u2013 4 April 2006, [[Tunbridge Wells]]) was a British journalist, and an acknowledged authority on [[circus]]es and the training of wild animals.<ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite news\n  | last = Stacey\n  | first = Don\n  | title = Obituaries: Edward Campbell\n  | newspaper = [[The Stage]]\n  | date = 2006-05-18\n  | url = http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/obituaries/feature.php/12653/edward-campbell\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060920063725/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/obituaries/feature.php/12653/edward-campbell\n  | archive-date = 2006-09-20\n  | accessdate = 2008-10-04}}</ref>\n\nCampbell began his journalistic career in the late 1930s with Kemsley Newspapers in Glasgow. He moved to [[Fleet Street]] in 1956, where he worked for the [[Evening Standard]], the [[Evening News (London)|Evening News]] and the [[Sunday Dispatch]].<ref name=\"Obit\"/><ref>[http://www.i-c-r.org.uk/publications/monographarchive/Monograph2.pdf Author information provided in an ICR Monograph]</ref>\n\nCampbell also authored books, among them ''Jungle Be Gentle'', the ghost-written \"autobiography\" of his friend, the [[Germany|German]] [[animal trainer]] Hans Brick, and ''The People of the Secret'', published by [[Idries Shah]]'s Octagon Press,<ref name = \"New Dawn\">{{cite web\n | author = Buratti\n | first = Robert\n | title = Quest for the People of the Secret\n | publisher = New Gnosis Communications Int. Pty Ltd\n | work = New Dawn (issue 74)\n | date = 2002\n | url = https://www.newdawnmagazine.com/articles/quest-for-the-people-of-the-secret\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171228233951/http://www.newdawnmagazine.com/articles/quest-for-the-people-of-the-secret\n | archive-date = 28 December 2017\n | url-status = live\n | accessdate = 7 April 2019\n}}</ref> under the [[pseudonym]] \"Ernest Scott\".<ref name=\"Obit\" /><ref>''The People of the Secret'', Octagon Press 1986, {{ISBN|0-86304-038-1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060920063725/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/obituaries/feature.php/12653/edward-campbell Obituary on thestage.co.uk]\n* [http://www.i-c-r.org.uk/publications/monographarchive/Monograph2.pdf Some Unusual Aspects of Communication] (Monograph authored by Campbell)\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Edward}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n:''For other persons named Edward Campbell, see [[Edward Campbell (disambiguation)]]''\n'''Edward Cranston Campbell''' (26 August 1916, [[Glasgow]] \u2013 4 April 2006, [[Tunbridge Wells]]) was a British journalist, and an acknowledged authority on [[circus]]es and the training of wild animals.<ref name=\"Obit\">{{cite news\n  | last = Stacey\n  | first = Don\n  | title = Obituaries: Edward Campbell\n  | newspaper = [[The Stage]]\n  | date = 2006-05-18\n  | url = http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/obituaries/feature.php/12653/edward-campbell\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060920063725/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/obituaries/feature.php/12653/edward-campbell\n  | archive-date = 2006-09-20\n  | accessdate = 2008-10-04}}</ref>\n\nCampbell began his journalistic career in the late 1930s with Kemsley Newspapers in Glasgow. He moved to [[Fleet Street]] in 1956, where he worked for the [[Evening Standard]], the [[Evening News (London)|Evening News]] and the [[Sunday Dispatch]].<ref name=\"Obit\"/><ref>[http://www.i-c-r.org.uk/publications/monographarchive/Monograph2.pdf Author information provided in an ICR Monograph]</ref>\n\nCampbell also authored books, among them ''Jungle Be Gentle'', the ghost-written \"autobiography\" of his friend, the [[Germany|German]] [[animal trainer]] Hans Brick, and ''The People of the Secret'', published by [[Idries Shah]]'s Octagon Press,<ref name = \"New Dawn\">{{cite web\n | author = Buratti\n | first = Robert\n | title = Quest for the People of the Secret\n | publisher = New Gnosis Communications Int. Pty Ltd\n | work = New Dawn (issue 74)\n | date = 2002\n | url = https://www.newdawnmagazine.com/articles/quest-for-the-people-of-the-secret\n | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171228233951/http://www.newdawnmagazine.com/articles/quest-for-the-people-of-the-secret\n | archive-date = 28 December 2017\n | url-status = live\n | accessdate = 7 April 2019\n}}</ref> under the [[pseudonym]] \"Ernest Scott\".<ref name=\"Obit\" /><ref>''The People of the Secret'', Octagon Press 1986, {{ISBN|0-86304-038-1}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060920063725/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/obituaries/feature.php/12653/edward-campbell Obituary on thestage.co.uk]\n* [http://www.i-c-r.org.uk/publications/monographarchive/Monograph2.pdf Some Unusual Aspects of Communication] (Monograph authored by Campbell)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Campbell, Edward}}\n[[Category:1916 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:British non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:British spiritual writers]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Campbell_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "Senna pendula", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Starr 070111-3260 Senna pendula.jpg\n|status =\n|status_system =\n|status_ref =\n|genus = Senna\n|species = pendula\n|authority = (Humb. & Bonpl. ex [[Carl Ludwig von Willdenow|Willd.]]) [[Howard Samuel Irwin|H.S.Irwin]] & [[Rupert Charles Barneby|Barneby]]\n|synonyms =\n}}\n\n'''''Senna pendula''''', also known as '''Easter cassia''', '''climbing cassia''', '''winter senna''' and '''valamuerto''',<ref>[https://keyserver.lucidcentral.org/weeds/data/media/Html/senna_pendula_var._glabrata.htm Senna pendula var. Glabrata] by Weeds of Australia (biosecurity Queensland edition), [[Queensland Government]]. Retrieved 13 April 2020</ref> is a plant of the [[Fabaceae]] family with a shrub habit that is native to [[South America]]. It used in various parts of the world as an [[ornamental plant]] and is an environmental [[weed]] in [[Australia]]. The flowers of this plant are yellow or greenish yellow and the name ''pendula'' means 'pendulous' or 'drooping'.<ref>Irwin, HS & Barneby, RC, 1982 Mem.New York Bot.Gard.35: 1-918 [in 2 parts] American Cassiinae</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Winter Senna (Senna pendula) flowers (28914825366).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Flower close-up]]\nIt is a spreading, scrambling or erect [[shrub]] that reaches 2-4 metres in height with multi-branched and arching stems and branches. Its single-compound, hairless leaves feature three to six duos of wide [[Leaflet (botany)|leaflet]]s that are 1-5 cm long and 5-20 mm wide with rounded tips and salient yellowish margins.<ref>[http://www.anbg.gov.au/cpbr/cd-keys/RFK7/key/RFK7/Media/Html/entities/Senna_pendula_var._glabrata.htm Senna pendula var. Glabrata] by Australian Tropical Rainforest Plants. Retrieved 13 April 2020</ref> \n\nIts bright yellow flowers, which are about 3 cm across, have five large [[petal]]s and are foaled in leafy clumps at the tips of the branches. The fruit is in a cylindrical [[Husk|pod]] (10-20 cm long and 6-12 mm wide) that hangs down. It flowers year round, but more prominently in [[Easter]], hence its common name.<ref> Irwin.H.S.& Barneby,R.C., 1982 Mem.N.Y.Bot.Gard.35(1 & 2):1-918 The American Cassiinae</ref>\n\n''Senna pendula'' is distinguished from ''[[Senna bicapsularis]]'' which has 3 pairs of leaflets on each leaf, while this one has 4-7 pairs of leaflets on each leaf and a gland between each pair of leaflets.\n\n==Invasive species==\nThe ''S. p. glabrata'' variety has become [[Naturalisation (biology)|naturalised]], and is also an environmental weed, in eastern [[Australia]] in the coastal and sub-coastal regions of south-eastern [[Queensland]] and [[New South Wales]], where it is found in [[watercourse]]s, gardens, disturbed sites, [[Barren vegetation|wasteland]]s, roadsides, closed forests, forest margins and urban [[bushland]].<ref>[https://weeds.brisbane.qld.gov.au/weeds/easter-cassia Easter cassia Senna pendula var. Glabrata] by the [[Brisbane City Council]] Weed Identification Tool. Retrieved 13 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Subspecies==\nThe plant features the following subspecies:<ref>Hyde, M.A., Wursten, B.T. & Ballings, P. (2013). Flora of Zimbabwe: Species information: Senna pendula var. glabrata.</ref>\n\n*''S. p. advena''\n*''S. p. ambigua''\n*''S. p. dolichandra''\n*''S. p. eriocarpa''\n*''S. p. glabrata''\n*''S. p. hemirostrata''\n*''S. p. indistincta''\n*''S. p. meticola''\n*''S. p. mission''\n*''S. p. ovalifolia''\n*''S. p. paludicola''\n*''S. p. pendula''\n*''S. p. praeandina''\n*''S. p. recondita''\n*''S. p. scandens''\n*''S. p. stahlii''\n*''S. p. tenuifolia''\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Starr 070321-6034 Senna pendula.jpg|Budding flowers\nFile:Starr 070321-6037 Senna pendula.jpg|Growing at a farmland\nFile:Starr 070111-3268 Senna pendula.jpg|[[Cut flower]]\nFile:Starr 070321-6035 Senna pendula.jpg|Seed pods\nFile:Starr 070321-6030 Senna pendula.jpg|Scrambling on a fence\nFile:Senna pendula (Willd.) H.S.Irwin ^ Barneby - Flickr - Alex Popovkin, Bahia, Brazil (3).jpg|Leaves closeup \nFile:Senna pendula (Willd.) H.S.Irwin ^ Barneby - Flickr - Alex Popovkin, Bahia, Brazil (6).jpg|Flower closeup\nFile:Starr 070111-3261 Senna pendula.jpg|Leaves and flowers\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Wikispecies|Senna pendula|''Senna pendula''}}\n{{Commons category|Senna pendula|''Senna pendula''}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q10370080}}\n\n[[Category:Senna|bicapsularis]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1982]]\n[[Category:Flora of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Flora of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Flora of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Flora of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Flora naturalised in Australia]]\n[[Category:Ornamental plants]]\n[[Category:Invasive plant species in Australia]]\n[[Category:Invasive plant species in South Africa]]\n[[Category:IUCN Red List least concern species]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n|image = Starr 070111-3260 Senna pendula.jpg\n|status =\n|status_system =\n|status_ref =\n|genus = Senna\n|species = pendula\n|authority = (Humb. & Bonpl. ex [[Carl Ludwig von Willdenow|Willd.]]) [[Howard Samuel Irwin|H.S.Irwin]] & [[Rupert Charles Barneby|Barneby]]\n|synonyms =\n}}\n\n'''''Senna pendula''''', also known as '''Easter cassia''', '''climbing cassia''', '''winter senna''' and '''valamuerto''',<ref>[https://keyserver.lucidcentral.org/weeds/data/media/Html/senna_pendula_var._glabrata.htm Senna pendula var. Glabrata] by Weeds of Australia (biosecurity Queensland edition), [[Queensland Government]]. Retrieved 13 April 2020</ref> is a plant of the [[Fabaceae]] family with a shrub habit that is native to [[South America]]. It used in various parts of the world as an [[ornamental plant]] and is an environmental [[weed]] in [[Australia]]. The flowers of this plant are yellow or greenish yellow and the name ''pendula'' means 'pendulous' or 'drooping'.<ref>Irwin, HS & Barneby, RC, 1982 Mem.New York Bot.Gard.35: 1-918 [in 2 parts] American Cassiinae</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Winter Senna (Senna pendula) flowers (28914825366).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Flower close-up]]\nIt is a spreading, scrambling or erect [[shrub]] that reaches 2-4 metres in height with multi-branched and arching stems and branches. Its single-compound, hairless leaves feature three to six duos of wide [[Leaflet (botany)|leaflet]]s that are 1-5 cm long and 5-20 mm wide with rounded tips and salient yellowish margins.<ref>[http://www.anbg.gov.au/cpbr/cd-keys/RFK7/key/RFK7/Media/Html/entities/Senna_pendula_var._glabrata.htm Senna pendula var. Glabrata] by Australian Tropical Rainforest Plants. Retrieved 13 April 2020</ref> \n\nIts bright yellow flowers, which are about 3 cm across, have five large [[petal]]s and are foaled in leafy clumps at the tips of the branches. The fruit is in a cylindrical [[Husk|pod]] (10-20 cm long and 6-12 mm wide) that hangs down. It flowers year round, but more prominently in [[Easter]], hence its common name.<ref> Irwin.H.S.& Barneby,R.C., 1982 Mem.N.Y.Bot.Gard.35(1 & 2):1-918 The American Cassiinae</ref>\n\n''Senna pendula'' is distinguished from ''[[Senna bicapsularis]]'' which has 3 pairs of leaflets on each leaf, while this one has 4-7 pairs of leaflets on each leaf and a gland between each pair of leaflets.\n\n==Invasive species==\nThe ''S. p. glabrata'' variety has become [[Naturalisation (biology)|naturalised]], and is also an environmental weed, in eastern [[Australia]] in the coastal and sub-coastal regions of south-eastern Queensland and New South Wales, where it is found in [[watercourse]]s, gardens, disturbed sites, [[Barren vegetation|wasteland]]s, roadsides, closed forests, forest margins and urban bushland.<ref>[https://weeds.brisbane.qld.gov.au/weeds/easter-cassia Easter cassia Senna pendula var. Glabrata] by the [[Brisbane City Council]] Weed Identification Tool. Retrieved 13 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Subspecies==\nThe plant features the following subspecies:<ref>Hyde, M.A., Wursten, B.T. & Ballings, P. (2013). Flora of Zimbabwe: Species information: Senna pendula var. glabrata.</ref>\n\n*''S. p. advena''\n*''S. p. ambigua''\n*''S. p. dolichandra''\n*''S. p. eriocarpa''\n*''S. p. glabrata''\n*''S. p. hemirostrata''\n*''S. p. indistincta''\n*''S. p. meticola''\n*''S. p. mission''\n*''S. p. ovalifolia''\n*''S. p. paludicola''\n*''S. p. pendula''\n*''S. p. praeandina''\n*''S. p. recondita''\n*''S. p. scandens''\n*''S. p. stahlii''\n*''S. p. tenuifolia''\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Starr 070321-6034 Senna pendula.jpg|Budding flowers\nFile:Starr 070321-6037 Senna pendula.jpg|Growing at a farmland\nFile:Starr 070111-3268 Senna pendula.jpg|[[Cut flower]]\nFile:Starr 070321-6035 Senna pendula.jpg|Seed pods\nFile:Starr 070321-6030 Senna pendula.jpg|Scrambling on a fence\nFile:Senna pendula (Willd.) H.S.Irwin ^ Barneby - Flickr - Alex Popovkin, Bahia, Brazil (3).jpg|Leaves closeup \nFile:Senna pendula (Willd.) H.S.Irwin ^ Barneby - Flickr - Alex Popovkin, Bahia, Brazil (6).jpg|Flower closeup\nFile:Starr 070111-3261 Senna pendula.jpg|Leaves and flowers\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Wikispecies|Senna pendula|''Senna pendula''}}\n{{Commons category|Senna pendula|''Senna pendula''}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q10370080}}\n\n[[Category:Senna|bicapsularis]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1982]]\n[[Category:Flora of Brazil]]\n[[Category:Flora of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Flora of Colombia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Bolivia]]\n[[Category:Flora of Paraguay]]\n[[Category:Flora of Argentina]]\n[[Category:Flora naturalised in Australia]]\n[[Category:Ornamental plants]]\n[[Category:Invasive plant species in Australia]]\n[[Category:Invasive plant species in South Africa]]\n[[Category:IUCN Red List least concern species]]\n", "name_user": "Zroota", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInvasive species", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Senna_pendula"}
{"title_page": "Edward C. Ratcliff", "text_new": "{{Underlinked|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Edward Craddock Ratcliff''' (16 December 1896 \u2013 July 1967) was a major twentieth-century English liturgical scholar.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*''The English Coronation Service'' (1936)\n*''The Book of Common Prayer: Its Making and Revisions'' (1949)\n*''The Coronation Service of Queen Elizabeth II'' (1953)\n*''From Uniformity to Unity'' (1962)\n\n== References ==\n*Obituary, ''The Times'', July 4, 1967.\n*''Edward Craddock Ratcliff: A Bibliography of His Published Works'' ([[Alcuin Club]], 1967)\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ratcliff, Edward C.}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n[[Category:Liturgists]]\n\n\n{{England-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Edward Craddock Ratcliff''' (16 December 1896 \u2013 July 1967) was a major twentieth-century English liturgical scholar.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*''The English Coronation Service'' (1936)\n*''The Book of Common Prayer: Its Making and Revisions'' (1949)\n*''The Coronation Service of Queen Elizabeth II'' (1953)\n*''From Uniformity to Unity'' (1962)\n\n== References ==\n*Obituary, ''The Times'', July 4, 1967.\n*''Edward Craddock Ratcliff: A Bibliography of His Published Works'' ([[Alcuin Club]], 1967)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ratcliff, Edward C.}}\n[[Category:1896 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of St John's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:English male writers]]\n[[Category:Liturgists]]\n\n\n{{England-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedunderlinkedtag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_C._Ratcliff"}
{"title_page": "Edward Buck (lawyer)", "text_new": "'''Edward Buck''' (October 6, 1814 \u2013 July 16, 1876) was an American lawyer and writer.\n\nBuck, the fifth son of Gurdon and Susannah (Manwaring) Buck, and a descendant of Gov. [[Gurdon Saltonstall]], of Connecticut, was born in New York City, Oct. 6, 1814.  He graduated from Yale College in 1835.  He studied law in New York, and began practice in that city in 1838. In 1843 he removed to Boston, where he continued actively engaged in his profession until his death. From 1854 his residence was in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover, Mass]]., where he died, July 16, 1876, in his 62nd year.  Buck was a frequent writer for the newspapers, and published in 1866 an important volume on ''Massachusetts Ecclesiastical Law'' (Boston, 8vo, 316 pp.). As a prominent Christian layman his interest in all educational and philanthropic matters was always intelligent and active.  He married, June 8, 1841, Elizabeth Greene, daughter of Hon. [[Samuel Hubbard (Massachusetts judge)|Samuel Hubbard]], of Boston, a Justice of the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court|Supreme Court of Massachusetts]]. She survived him with their two children, a son and a daughter. The son graduated Yale in 1870.\n\n{{yaleobit}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fg|92104976}}\n*''[[iarchive:massachusettsecc00buck|Massachusetts Ecclesiastical Law]]'' by Buck\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buck, Edward}}\n[[Category:1814 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from New York City]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts lawyers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Edward Buck''' (October 6, 1814 \u2013 July 16, 1876) was an American lawyer and writer.\n\nBuck, the fifth son of Gurdon and Susannah (Manwaring) Buck, and a descendant of Gov. [[Gurdon Saltonstall]], of Connecticut, was born in New York City, Oct. 6, 1814.  He graduated from Yale College in 1835.  He studied law in New York, and began practice in that city in 1838. In 1843 he removed to Boston, where he continued actively engaged in his profession until his death. From 1854 his residence was in [[Andover, Massachusetts|Andover, Mass]]., where he died, July 16, 1876, in his 62nd year.  Buck was a frequent writer for the newspapers, and published in 1866 an important volume on ''Massachusetts Ecclesiastical Law'' (Boston, 8vo, 316 pp.). As a prominent Christian layman his interest in all educational and philanthropic matters was always intelligent and active.  He married, June 8, 1841, Elizabeth Greene, daughter of Hon. [[Samuel Hubbard (Massachusetts judge)|Samuel Hubbard]], of Boston, a Justice of the [[Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court|Supreme Court of Massachusetts]]. She survived him with their two children, a son and a daughter. The son graduated Yale in 1870.\n\n{{yaleobit}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{fg|92104976}}\n*''[[iarchive:massachusettsecc00buck|Massachusetts Ecclesiastical Law]]'' by Buck\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buck, Edward}}\n[[Category:1814 births]]\n[[Category:1876 deaths]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from New York City]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts lawyers]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_Buck_(lawyer)"}
{"title_page": "List of people from Frankston", "text_new": "{{dynamic list}}\nThis is a list of notable past and present people from the [[City of Frankston]] in [[Melbourne]], [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], [[Australia]]. It incorporates the City of Frankston localities and suburbs of [[Carrum Downs, Victoria|Carrum Downs]], [[Frankston, Victoria|Frankston]], Frankston East, Frankston Heights, [[Frankston North, Victoria|Frankston North]], [[Frankston South, Victoria|Frankston South]], Kananook, [[Karingal, Victoria|Karingal]], [[Langwarrin, Victoria|Langwarrin]], [[Langwarrin South, Victoria|Langwarrin South]], Long Island, Mount Erin, [[Olivers Hill, Victoria|Olivers Hill]], [[Sandhurst, Victoria|Sandhurst]], [[Seaford, Victoria|Seaford]] and [[Skye, Victoria|Skye]]. The [[demonym]] for a person from Frankston is a \"Frankstonian\".\n\n==Arts==\n*[[Rick Amor]] \u2013 [[painter]] and [[sculptor]]<ref name=FstonHoF2010>[http://www.frankston.vic.gov.au/Arts_Culture_and_Heritage/Frankstons_Hall_of_Fame/Hall_of_Fame_Inductees_2010/index.aspx Hall of Fame Inductees 2010] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314185112/http://www.frankston.vic.gov.au/Arts_Culture_and_Heritage/Frankstons_Hall_of_Fame/Hall_of_Fame_Inductees_2010/index.aspx |date=14 March 2011 }}. [[City of Frankston]]. Accessed: 22 October 2010.</ref><ref name=FstonLeader4Oct10>Carlton, Donna. 4 October 2010. \"[http://frankston-leader.whereilive.com.au/news/story/recognition-for-frankstons-latest-achievers/ Hall of fame recognises Frankston's latest achievers] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706113529/http://frankston-leader.whereilive.com.au/news/story/recognition-for-frankstons-latest-achievers/ |date=6 July 2011 }}\". ''[[Leader Community Newspapers|Frankston Leader]]''. [[News Limited]]. Accessed: 22 October 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.awm.gov.au/people/P25663/ FRick Amor]. [[Australian War Memorial]]. [[Department of Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Department of Veterans' Affairs]] [[Government of Australia]]. Retrieved 28 August 2016</ref>\n*[[William Leslie Bowles]] \u2013 sculptor and [[medal]]list<ref>Underhill, Nancy D. H. (1979). \"Bowles, William Leslie (1885\u20131954)\". ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'' (7). [[Melbourne University Publishing|Melbourne University Press]] ([http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/bowles-william-leslie-5313 HTML version]). Accessed: 23 October 2010.</ref><ref>[https://www.awm.gov.au/people/P65019/ William Leslie Bowles]. [[Australian War Memorial]]. [[Department of Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Department of Veterans' Affairs]] [[Government of Australia]]. Retrieved 28 August 2016</ref>\n*[[Raymond Boultwood Ewers]] \u2013 sculptor<ref>[https://www.awm.gov.au/people/P65055/ Raymond Boultwood Ewers]. [[Australian War Memorial]]. [[Department of Veterans' Affairs (Australia)|Department of Veterans' Affairs]] [[Government of Australia]]. Retrieved 28 August 2016</ref>\n*[[Walter Langcake]] \u2013 sculptor and [[Woodturning|woodturner]]{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}\n*[[Daryl Lindsay|Sir Daryl Lindsay]] \u2013 painter and Director of the [[National Gallery of Victoria]] from 1942-1956 (lived at Mulberry Hill in [[Langwarrin South, Victoria|Langwarrin South]])<ref name=FstonHoF2008>[http://www.frankston.vic.gov.au/Arts_Culture_and_Heritage/Frankstons_Hall_of_Fame/Hall_of_Fame_Inductees_2008/index.aspx Hall of Fame Inductees 2008] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110314213115/http://www.frankston.vic.gov.au/Arts_Culture_and_Heritage/Frankstons_Hall_of_Fame/Hall_of_Fame_Inductees_2008/index.aspx |date=14 March 2011 }}. [[City of Frankston]]. Accessed: 22 October 2010.</ref><ref name=FstonWeekly7Oct2008>Morris, Mike. 7 October 2008. \"[http://www.frankstonweekly.com.au/news/local/news/general/fame-finds-a-home-in-frankston/1327253.aspx Fame finds a home in Franston]\". ''Frankston Weekly'' (formerly the ''Frankston Independent''). [[Fairfax Media]].Accessed: 22 October 2010.</ref>\n*[[Richard Linton]] \u2013 painter, studio was formerly located in [[Frankston, Victoria|Frankston]] Central Business District (CBD) and is now just south of it at the Morningstar Estate vineyard<ref>Where it all began: The history of Morningstar Estate. Morningstar Estate. ([http://www.heritage.rose.org.au/file/357 HTML version] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706125717/http://www.heritage.rose.org.au/file/357 |date=6 July 2011 }}) Accessed: 22 October 2010.</ref>\n\n==Business and society==\n*[[Beryl Beaurepaire|Dame Beryl Beaurepaire]], [[Order of Australia|AC]], [[Order of the British Empire|DBE]] \u2013 [[philanthropy|philanthropist]] and [[women's rights]] campaigner<ref name=FstonHoF2009 /><ref name=FstonWeekley06Oct09 /><ref name=FstonLeader17Oct09/><ref name=HeraldSun30Aug09/>\n*[[Anthony Di Pietro]] \u2013 businessman and Chairman of [[Melbourne Victory FC]] from 2011\u2013present{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n*[[Laurence Hartnett|Sir Laurence Hartnett]], [[Order of the British Empire|CBE]] \u2013 [[automotive industry|automotive]] pioneer, known as the \"father of [[Holden]]\" (Hartnett Drive in [[Seaford, Victoria|Seaford]] is named in his honour)<ref name=FstonHoF2009/><ref name=FstonWeekley06Oct09 /><ref name=FstonLeader17Oct09 /><ref name=HeraldSun30Aug09 />\n*[[John Holland (engineer)|Sir John Holland]], [[Order of Australia|AC]] \u2013 philanthropist, [[engineering]] and [[construction]] magnate; founder of [[John Holland Group]]<ref>Carman, Gerry. 4 June 2009. \"[http://www.theage.com.au/national/nationbuilder-reached-out-to-others-20090603-bvpr.html Nation-builder reached out to others]\". ''[[The Age]]''. [[Fairfax Media]]. Accessed 22 October 2010.</ref>\n*[[Josiah Humphrey]] \u2013 co-founder and [[CEO]] of app development company [[Appster]]<ref>[http://appbusinesspodcast.com/josiah-humphrey-appsters/ Josiah Humphrey of Appsters]. appbusinesspodcast.com. Contenta Mobile Limited. Retrieved 10 September 2015