. General Sir Dallas Brooks]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]], [[Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Royal Victorian Order|KCVO]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Venerable Order of Saint John|KStJ]] \u2013 19th [[Governor of Victoria]] from 1949-1963, and the [[General]] of the [[Royal Marines]] from 1945-1949<ref>de Serville, P.H. (1993). \"Brooks, Sir Dallas. (1896 - 1966)\". ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'' (13). [[Melbourne University Publishing|Melbourne University Press]]; pp 267-268. ([http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A130302b.htm HTML Version]). Accessed: 24 October 2010.</ref>\n*[[Stanley Bruce|Rt Hon. Lord Stanley Bruce]], [[Order of the Companions of Honour|CH]], [[Military Cross|MC]], [[Royal Society|FRS]], [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] \u2013 8th [[Prime Minister of Australia]] from 1923-1929 (lived at Bruce Manor in [[Frankston, Victoria|Frankston]], before moving to [[The Lodge (Australia)|The Lodge]] in [[Canberra]])<ref name=FstonHoF2010 /><ref name=FstonLeader4Oct10 />\n*[[Harold Winthrop Clapp|Sir Harold W. Clapp]], [[Order of the British Empire|KBE]] \u2013 [[Victorian Railways]] Chairman of Commissioners from 1920-1939<ref>Adam-Smith, Patsy. (1981). \"Clapp, Sir Harold W. (1875 - 1952)\". ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'' (8). [[Melbourne University Publishing|Melbourne University Press]]; pp 1-3. ([http://www.adb.online.anu.edu.au/biogs/A080002b.htm HTML version]). Accessed: 23 October 2010.</ref>\n*[[Chris Crewther]], [[Member of Parliament|MP]] \u2013 Member of the Parliament of Australia for the Division of Dunkley from 2016\u2013present (he has lived in Frankston, Frankston South, Seaford and Mount Eliza), as well as former small business owner, CEO, and international lawyer through the [[United Nation]]s.<ref>[http://vtr.aec.gov.au/HouseDivisionPage-20499-210.htm Tally room - Dunkley] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727113648/http://vtr.aec.gov.au/HouseDivisionPage-20499-210.htm |date=27 July 2016 }}. [[Australian Electoral Commission]]. Retrieved 2 August 2016</ref>\n*[[James Fenton (Australian politician)|Hon. James Fenton]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]] \u2013 Postmaster-General of Australia (precursor to [[Minister for Communications (Australia)|Minister for Communications]]), oversaw establishment of the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] in 1932<ref>Robertson, J. R. (1981). \"Fenton, James Edward (1864\u20131950)\". ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'' (8). [[Melbourne University Publishing|Melbourne University Press]]. ([http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/fenton-james-edward-6155/text10571 HTML version]). Accessed: 08 January 2014.</ref>\n*[[Rupert Hamer|Hon. Sir Rupert Hamer]], [[Order of Australia|AC]], [[Order of St Michael and St George|KCMG]], [[Efficiency Decoration|ED]] \u2013 39th [[Premier of Victoria]] from 1972-1981, anti-[[discrimination]] and [[Environmental movement|environmental]] campaigner<ref>Frankston Coastal Discovery Trail. [[City of Frankston]]; p 4. ([http://www.frankston.vic.gov.au/library/scripts/objectifyMedia.aspx?file=pdf/225/93.pdf&siteID=18&str_title=Coastal%20Arts%20Discovery%20Trail.pdf PDF version] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504045821/http://www.frankston.vic.gov.au/library/scripts/objectifyMedia.aspx?file=pdf%2F225%2F93.pdf&siteID=18&str_title=Coastal%20Arts%20Discovery%20Trail.pdf |date=4 May 2013 }}). Accessed: 22 October 2010.</ref>\n*[[Jeff Kennett|Hon. Jeff Kennett]], [[Order of Australia|AC]] \u2013 43rd Premier of Victoria from 1992-1999, [[mental health]] campaigner and media commentator<ref name=HeraldSun02Dec2013 /><ref name=HeraldSun23Oct2013>Kennett, Jeff. 23 October 2013. [http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/opinion/frankstons-the-place-to-be-as-the-next-election-comes-closer/story-fni0ffsx-1226744805372#mm-breached Frankston's the place to be as the next election comes closer]. ''[[Herald Sun]]''. [[News Limited]]. Accessed: 08 January 2014